2. Preprocess unstructured data to make it consumable for model training.¶

  • ### A. Eliminate All special Characters and Numbers
  • ### B. Lowercase all textual data
  • ### C. Remove all Stopwords
  • ### D. Remove all extra white spaces
In [5]:
def pre_process_over_text(text):

    # Cleaning the urls
    text = re.sub(r'https?://\S+|www\.\S+', '', text)

    # Cleaning the html elements
    text = re.sub(r'<.*?>', '', text)

    # Eliminate All special Characters and Numbers
    text = re.sub(r'[^A-Za-z\s]', "", text)

    # Lowercase all textual data
    text = text.lower()

    # Remove all extra white spaces
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', " ", text).strip()

    tokens = word_tokenize(text)

    tokens = [lm.lemmatize(word) for word in tokens if not contractions.fix(word) in stopwords.words('english')]

    return ' '.join(tokens)

# Function to show WordCloud for default 100 words
def get_top_n_words(model, all_features, n=100):

    top_features=''

    features = np.argsort(model.feature_importances_)[::-1]

    for i in features[0:n]:
        top_features+=all_features[i]
        top_features+=','

    wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color = "white", colormap = 'viridis', width = 2000,
                              height = 1000).generate(top_features)

    # Display the generated image:
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation = 'bilinear')
    plt.figure(1, figsize = (20, 15), frameon='equal')
    plt.title(f'Top {n} features WordCloud', fontsize = 30)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()
In [13]:
# Function to print the classification report and get confusion matrix in a proper format
def metrics_score(test_actual, test_predicted, train_actual, train_predicted, model_name, model_lists):

    train_acc = accuracy_score(train_actual,train_predicted)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(test_actual,test_predicted)
    print('Train Accuracy Score:',train_acc)
    print('Test Accuracy Score:',test_acc)

    print("\nClassification Matrix:\n",classification_report(test_actual, test_predicted))

    plt.figure(figsize = (25, 15))
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(test_actual, test_predicted), annot = True,  fmt = '.1f')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

    model_lists.append([model_name, train_acc, test_acc, precision_score(test_actual,test_predicted, average='micro'), recall_score(test_actual,test_predicted, average='micro'), f1_score(test_actual,test_predicted, average='micro')])

From above models, LGBMClassifier has performed good in compare to other models as per the different scores, like accuracy_score, recall, precision, f1 score, and more.

Hyperparameters like num_leaves, max_depth, n_estimators, learning_rate have tuned model for better performance and more different params can also use for increasing performance. Increasing 'n_estimators' more will increase more score, but which will bring more time to fit and train.

In this block, F1-Score and Recall has been given higher precedence. F1-score provides class-wise performance which helps to improve the model and prediction much better.

$$ F1 Score = \frac{2 * Precision * Recall}{Precision + Recall} $$$$ Recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN} $$$$ Precision = \frac{TP}{TP + FP} $$

def pre_process_over_text(text):

    remove_punc_dict = dict((ord(punc), None) for punc in string.punctuation)
    # Lowercase all textual data
    text = text.lower().translate(remove_punc_dict)

    # Remove all extra white spaces
    text = re.sub(r'\s+', " ", text).strip()

    #tokenize data
    text = word_tokenize(text)

    text = [spell(word) for word in text]

    # lemmatize the data
    text = [lm.lemmatize(word) for word in text]

    return ' '.join(text)

def chat():
    flag=True
    print(emojize("BOT:robot_face:: Hello:wave:, My name is ZhangZetsu.",language='alias'))
    sleep(0.5)
    while flag:
        user_response = input()
        print(emojize(f"YOU:information_desk_person:: {user_response}",language='alias'))
        if user_response is None or len(user_response.strip())==0:
            print(emojize("BOT:robot_face:: Please enter details!!!",language='alias'))
            sleep(0.5)
            continue
        pred = label_mapping[svc.predict(tf_cb.transform([pre_process_over_text(user_response)]).toarray())][0]
        if pred == 'exit':
            flag = False
        print(emojize("BOT:robot_face::",language='alias'),np.random.choice(tag_resp_dict.get(pred)))
        sleep(0.5)
